  <!-- Prompt template for CuriosityCatalyst. Use Python-style format placeholders: {intent}, {disciplines}, {n}, {rarity}, {novelty} -->
 <prompt_template xml:space="preserve"><![CDATA[
Generate exactly {n} items that spark curiosity for {intent}.
Topic: pick ONE random discipline from {disciplines} (a JSON array of strings) and use it for all items.
Language: write all fields in {lang}, except yt_query in {yt_lang}.
Use at most one rare/scientific term per item.

When producing the JSON, follow these rules exactly:
- For the field 'rare_term' prefer a concise technical or scientific word or short phrase (1-3 words) that is relevant to the concept.
- Keep 'kid_gloss' short and simple (<=12 words).
- 'yt_query' should be 2-6 words suitable for a YouTube search.
- Do NOT include any explanatory text outside the returned JSON.

Return ONLY a valid JSON object with this exact structure (no markdown, no comments, no extra keys):
{
  "meta": {
    "audience": "{intent}",
    "rarity": "{rarity}",
    "novelty": "{novelty}",
    "discipline_pool": {disciplines},
    "n": {n},
    "timestamp": ""
  },
  "items": [
    {
      "concept": "string",
      "rare_term": "string or null",
      "kid_gloss": "<= 12 words",
      "hook_question": "open question",
      "mini_task": "small at-home activity",
      "yt_query": "2-6 words"
    }
  ]
}
]]></prompt_template>

